# Grid-First Layout

Use **CSS Grid** for page and section structure. Use **Flexbox** only when Grid is a poor fit.

This project uses **Tailwind v4** — prefer `grid`, `grid-cols-*`, `gap-*`, and `place-*` utilities.

## Default to Grid

Use Grid for:

- Page sections and multi-column layouts
- Card grids, stat rows, and feature lists
- Header/footer structure with distinct columns
- Any 2D layout (rows **and** columns)

```js
// ❌ BAD — flex for a structural multi-column section
<div className="flex flex-wrap gap-8 sm:flex-row">...</div>

// ✅ GOOD — grid for structural layout
<div className="grid gap-8 sm:grid-cols-2">...</div>
```

```js
// ✅ GOOD — page-level structure
<div className="mx-auto grid max-w-6xl items-center gap-12 md:grid-cols-2">...</div>
```

## Flex only when required

Use Flex sparingly for:

- Single-axis alignment inside one grid cell (e.g. center an icon in a box)
- Inline groups that must not wrap into a grid (button groups, nav item clusters)
- `flex-1` / `grow` behavior inside a parent that is already Grid-based
- Third-party components that require flex (e.g. Clerk `UserButton` wrappers)

```js
// ✅ OK — flex inside a grid cell for inline controls
<div className="flex items-center gap-3">
  <Button>Sign in</Button>
  <Button>Sign up</Button>
</div>
```

## Avoid

- `flex` on outer section wrappers that define columns or rows
- `flex-wrap` as a substitute for responsive grids
- Nested flex containers where one `grid` parent would suffice
- Mixing competing layout models at the same structural level without reason

## Checklist for new layout work

- [ ] Section/column structure uses `grid` first
- [ ] Responsive breakpoints use `grid-cols-*`, not flex direction swaps
- [ ] Flex is limited to inner alignment or unavoidable one-dimensional cases
- [ ] Gaps use `gap-*` on the grid parent, not margin hacks between flex children
